\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f0  Tuesday, 9/11}{\f0 
\par The phone rings early and wakes me up. It\rquote s Richard wanting to know if I\rquote ve heard the news.  He gives me the headlines and I hang up and turn on the radio, not 
wanting to wake Arthur who is still sleeping; his heart rhythms are irregular and I don\rquote 
t want to risk the unknown effects of sudden alarming events. Timing, information, priorities, language.  Everything has changed in the beat of a heart.  All day we sit
 in front of the TV, trying to determine the difference between the real and the surreal. Yesterday they seemed clearly legible categories.   During the day we watch Peter Jennings.  At night we watch Ted Koppel and Charlie Rose and the apparently thought
f
ul cross-section of experts they interview.  For the first time in my life, I am grateful to these men for their candid questions and calm demeanor, listening through them for any new shred of analysis or differing perspective that might import an enlight
ened moment. 
\par 
\par }{\b\f0 Thursday, 9/13}{\f0 
\par Woke up at least ten times during the night...finally rose, with jaw aching from stress.  Another day glued to the TV, still unable to focus, summon the will to think about previously intended work.  My British friend, having b
een a child during the Second World War, emails me condolences & writes \'93One gets used to anything, finally, my dear Caterina...\'94  I cannot find words to write back.  I don\rquote t want to learn to \'93get used to anything\'94. 
\par 
\par }{\b\f0 Friday, 9/14}{\f0 
\par Email from Manny, 14, just starting his freshman year at Stuyvesant High School in Manhattan, 4 blocks from the WTC...comes in on the subway from Brooklyn every morning...arrived on the 11th about an hour before the first tower was hit.   He writes:  \'93
I was in school when a voice 
crackled over the loudspeaker reporting that one of the World Trade Centers had exploded for some reason or another.  We looked outside but, being on the north side, could see nothing except a constant stream of fire engines, ambulances, and police cars r
ushing down the West Side Highway.  At this point the depth of the situation hadn\rquote 
t sunk in to any of us, so we all proceeded to third period.  It was there that my teacher, being the heartless, ignorant pig that he is, committed a series of acts rivaled in
 evil only by the suicide crashes themselves: first, he closed the blinds and turned the lights off to prevent anything from distracting us from his precious lesson, the most important thing in the universe.  Then, he proceeded to resume the lesson of the
 day.  And, to top it all off, when a girl innocently asked what was going on outside, he responded by saying that \lquote the World Trade Center was bombed once before; how was this any different or more important?\rquote \'94  }{\b\f0\ul 
\par }{\f0 \tab I admire Manny\rquote s disgust and am relieved that he didn\rquote t buy into the authority sham.
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f0 
\par }{\b\f0 Monday, 9/17  }{\f0 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 
Six days since the attack.  Decide not to start the day with TV.  Only hear NPR when crossing the city by car. Torn between the need to stay abreast of latest developments and its opposite\emdash to reclai
m some simple daily rituals. Compelled only by personal contact: email, telephone calls, shared texts\emdash 
emotional, spiritual, political, medical information being passed around.  Warnings of computer viruses. Reading in all directions, trying to educate myse
lf, understanding huge gaps of information...and our willingness not to know.  Looking at the paper and wondering which of today\rquote s stories have been planted to soften us up, how much of it is propaganda...and whose?
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f0 
\par }{\b\f0 Thursday, 9/20
\par }\pard \ql \fi-80\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 When I open my notebook 
to track what is beginning to come through in the media, I find two pieces of paper.  One has a printed quote from Simone Weil.  The other is a faded xerox of pages 134 & 135\emdash the final section of a discussion of H.D.\rquote 
s writing by Marianne Moore, which ends with this distinction:  \'93...we have heroics which do not confuse transcendence with domination and which, in their indestructibleness, are the core of tranquility and of intellectual equilibrium.\'94
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\b\f0 
\par Saturday, 9/22}{\f0 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 I partly blank out on & partly recognize t
he excited voices of the guys who do the play-by-play broadcasts of football games every weekend, all autumn long. Their excitement leaks under my study door and then I realize it\rquote s actually media reporters interviewing CNN\rquote 
s military strategist.  They are
 yelling out their questions at him like stock exchange traders; they are trading bomb tonnage statistics.  Minutes later, it IS the football game...language sets rattling on, from channel to channel, with the same sense of urgency.
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f0 \bullet \tab 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 In today\rquote s Arts section of the paper, Steven Winn reviews John O\rquote Keefe\rquote 
s currently running play on Robert Graves and Laura Riding Jackson.  The two principle characters are described as \'93A haunted Graves\'94 and \'93the self-dramatizing writer Laura Riding\'94.  O\rquote Keefe, we are told, has \'93
cut and fit the historical record to keener dramatic purpose\'94.  The story ends with this comment: \'93Graves\rquote  terrible memories of the trenches hover and shadow everything.  \lquote I liked the feeling of really being frightened,\rquote 
 Graves says with a dreamy intensity.  Nothing can ever be the same after living through a war.\'94
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\b\f0 
\par Monday, 9/24 }{\f0  
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 Megan calls with an extra ticket to the Friday night Giants game.  She knows from an earlier conversation that I\rquote ve
 been dying to see Barry Bonds in-the-flesh, against the backdrop of the new baseball stadium just recently plunked down right at the edge of the Bay.  Megan\rquote s family has tickets because her son, Reese\emdash 
whose parenting she shares with Bob and her partner, Angie (Reese\rquote s birth-mother)\emdash is scheduled to sing \'93The Star-spangled Banner\'94 with the SF Boys choir, who\rquote ve been chosen to open the game\rquote s festivities.  Angie\rquote 
s seat is now mine because she must cover third base for The Flying Trouts\emdash her own softball team\emdash on Friday night.  Bob, my long-time friend and Reese\rquote 
s father, is coming along too so we decide to meet at the entrance early and walk up the various ramps and through as many tiers and seating charts as the door guards will allow, just to check-out the cro
wd, the angle of visibility from behind home-plate, the famous garlic fries & Krispy Kreme donuts & the Polish sausage varieties for later purchase.  We end up just below the giant fielder\rquote 
s mitt next to the monster COKE bottle sculpture pouring continuous neon.
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f0 
\par }\pard \ql \li851\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin851\itap0 {\i\f0 And the rocket\rquote s red glare
\par The bombs bursting in air.
\par Gave proof through the night 
\par that our flag was still there.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 
\par Down on the field, the children\rquote s matching red knitted t-shirts seem to hold them upright as their choirboy voices pierce the air with the song\rquote s final question.  We can barely see them, from our perch in the open bleachers.  
