\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 Earlier in the week, Bob and I bump into each other at a friend\rquote 
s reading at City Lights and decide to have dinner together afterwards at one of our favorite 
restaurants in North Beach, a place called The Helmand (named for the longest river in Afghanistan), with its exotic cuisine of brown-sugared pumpkin and melting eggplant, where the lamb shanks fall off the bone every time.  Most of the happy eaters are a
lready digging-in when we come through the door.  We sit down amidst a full house of regulars who\rquote 
ve gathered to show solidarity with Daud and the local Afghanistani community.  We are told that two days before, someone ripped away the beautiful curved tubular awning leading to the door of his restaurant.  They\rquote 
d spat at the front window and yelled insults at him as he stood behind it.  But we were lucky. A week had passed since September 11 and people were beginning to gain a little equilibrium.  A guy from
 a neighboring table was passing the hat, collecting money for families of firemen killed in the Twin Towers collapse. We opened our wallets gratefully and breathed in an air filled with the scent of turmeric.
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f0 
\par }{\b\f0 Thursday, 9/27}{\f0 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 My Pilates instructor tells me
 that two planes have crashed into the airport terminal in Rome, so I rush home to turn on the TV, assuming the story will be covered.   I feel how Rome is my second home; I\rquote m worried for friends just as I\rquote 
d be for friends in NYC.  Over the next hour\rquote s viewing, I see only the last half of a single-sentence headline moving\emdash once\emdash across the bottom of the screen.  It tells me only that the crash was in Milano\emdash 
foggy air field, smaller plane turning Left instead of Right, causing collision. Not a terrorist action.  Meanwhile, I\rquote ve begun to notice the odd pecking order of media events and begin to write down the language: 
\par 
\par \'93Military stocks UP on Wall St.\'94  marches by next to \'93Rush Limbaugh says he\rquote s going deaf...will be completely so within two months\'94\emdash this news s
trip, looped-in, over and over, with major world events.  Rush gets equal billing, that morning, with Colin Powell.  Fifteen minutes later, a CNN reporter agrees with his interview subject, \'93We should speak with one voice.\'94 
\par 
\par \'93Only ten percent do not support the President...who ARE all these people, anyway?\'94 the excited voice of the sportscaster asks his news buddy.  Later, reporting the 2nd day air strike, a voice narrates sound bites behind the images: \'93
No British presence. It\rquote s all an American show\'94;  \'93New chief of \lquote homeland\rquote  defense, Tom Ridge.\'94  Since when did \'93homeland\'94
 enter our description of the U.S.?  I get a Second World War feeling at the back of my neck...what }{\i\f0 was}{\f0  that German word? \tab \tab \tab 
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\b\f0 
\par Friday, 9/28}{\f0 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0  I keep thinking about Oppen...why I\rquote ve persis
tently remembered his voice reading his poems, over these last days since September 11.  It was just before Christmas in 1966, when I first heard him read.  It had been snowing heavily for several days and the sidewalks in front of St. Marks Poetry Projec
t had been shoveled and re/shoveled at least three times in twenty-four hours. I was more than a week overdue with my first child and wanted to believe in the possibility of continuing.  In Oppen\rquote 
s low voice, that night, I could hear no easy hope...but immense pain, rage, scepticism, resistance\emdash unsupported by the theatre of rhetoric.  Every word seemed fought for\emdash 
a poetry discovered, cut apart, let go, repositioned.  Certainly a poetry that left ease behind.  
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 It may be that, even then, I could trust him because he left us with no place for guile or chosen innocence. It was a severity I\rquote 
d managed to avoid until then. I had no choice but to face a new level of difficulty, holding the dualistic claims of inevitable tragedy, while knowing I wanted to persist and to make a writing of my own signature.  In Oppen\rquote 
s work I heard a voice of such immense gravity and fragmentation and coherence that it seemed to eclipse all I\rquote d been drawn to in those dazzling and glamorous and witty New York days.  There was no rush int
o print, no performance or sense of writing for applause.  Instead of facility, I heard words struggling up out of silence.  The survival of Ishmael, of Job: \'93And I only am escaped alone to tell thee.\'94 
\par }\pard \ql \fi360\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 He\rquote d survived, but there was no hubris in it.  Just the need\emdash this unavoidable claim on him\emdash 
to make a true human accounting of his life, severe, even-handed in its carefully joined and separated parts.  He was telling the fact of his witness and his writing practice\emdash a hand-carpentered artifact with the sound of its own making\emdash 
poised at the edge of a vision that found no comfort in the flag-imbedded codes of a single voice.  The words were minimal; the decisions of line and silence gave evidence of breathing and of presence in that silence\emdash empty tempo even\emdash in w
hich to rest and to take in what had accrued, before rushing forward...weighted with news of still being here, in spite of everything he\rquote d seen and heard as a soldier in the world.  
\par }\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {\f0 \bullet \tab 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 Friday, I hear a first alternative view announced over the news: \'93Doctors w/o Borders condemns Pres. Bush\rquote s attack on Afghanistan. Dismisses 
\lquote million dollar food gift\rquote  as propaganda. General, interviewed on food drop, admits that packets will be dropped deep in the mountains.  Very heavy parcels will have to be found and carted away by refugees.\'94
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 We piece together what we read, who said what on which program.  We forward all information from alternative news sources.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f0 
\par Tuesday, 9/30}{\f0 
\par Sunday morning I go into Top of the Hill market\emdash our local \'93momma & poppa\'94 store\emdash to thank Frank for the two tickets he passed on to us for yesterday\rquote 
s Giants game and to tell him my version of why our team lost their chance to move into the finals.
\par \tab  \'93I heard it was a real lousy game,\'94 he says.  \'93Sorry about that.\'94
\par \tab \'93Hey, Frank,\'94 I tell him, \'93it was fun anyway. I }{\i\f0 already}{\f0  got to see Barry hit his 67th Friday night, so what the hell...it was just fun to be there and watch the guys working out.  I think I\rquote m turning into a fan!\'94 

\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f0 Frank and his brother lease the store space on the ground flo
or of the corner building. Hanging from the second floor window of the apartment above them\emdash almost touching the sidewalk and almost covering the fruit-filled window\emdash 
is an immense American flag, suspended vertically, with its red-and-white stripes looking like a great collapsed tent or awning.  It is major code language and I speculate that, in some sense, it must make Frank\rquote 
s older brother, Sal, feel safe.  But Frank is more sceptical than Sal. If I were to ask him about it, he\rquote d probably go into a state of quizzical ambivalence\emdash his left eyebrow raised in silent comment above an otherwise boyish grin.
\par I have to talk extra-loud. Frank is almost deaf, after a series of operations, performed in the last few years before he turned thirty-five. No one is in the store, at the moment, so he doesn\rquote 
t have to watch the mirror trained on the back aisles.  We begin to talk about the pleasure of watching baseball on home turf at the new stadium\emdash how its architecture gives everyone a shot at views of the bridge and the wate
